Sure. If the user's date is input as `mm-dd-yyyy`, you can use the following code to convert it to a sentence with the format `Weekday, Month Day, Year. Month must be written out, and the sentence must end with a period`.

To do this, you can use the `java.text.SimpleDateFormat` class to parse the user's date and extract the components. Then, you can use string concatenation to construct the output sentence. Here is the code:

public static void main(String[] args) {
    String inputDate = "07-09-1923"; // user's date input in mm-dd-yyyy format
    SimpleDateFormat sdf = new SimpleDateFormat("MM-dd-yyyy");
    Date date = null;
    try {
        date = sdf.parse(inputDate);
    } catch (ParseException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
    }
    if (date != null) {
        Calendar calendar = Calendar.getInstance();
        calendar.setTime(date);
        String dayOfWeek = calendar.getDisplayName(Calendar.DAY_OF_WEEK, Calendar.SHORT, Locale.ENGLISH);
        int day = calendar.get(Calendar.DAY_OF_MONTH);
        String month = calendar.getDisplayName(Calendar.MONTH, Calendar.SHORT, Locale.ENGLISH);
        int year = calendar.get(Calendar.YEAR);
        String sentence = dayOfWeek + ", " + month + " " + day + ", " + year + ". " + month; // construct the output sentence
        System.out.println(sentence);
    }
}

This code will produce the output sentence `Sun, Jul 9, 1923. July`.
